benchmark_config.jira_title: Implement/Test API: GET /1.0/kb/accounts/{accountId}/emails/{accountEmailId}/auditLogsWithHistory - Retrieve account email audit logs with history by id

covered: Core acceptance criteria: success (200) and JSON array response covered (TC01, TC16).
Empty responses and state variations: empty audit list and empty DB handled (TC02, TC18).
Resource-not-found handling (404) for missing account or account email (TC03, TC04, TC19).
Input validation / bad path parameters (400) and simple attack vectors: invalid UUID formats and SQLi/XSS attempts (TC05, TC06, TC13, TC14).
Authentication negative cases: missing and invalid authentication return 401 (TC07, TC08).
Resilience and downstream errors: service unavailable and gateway timeout scenarios covered (TC09, TC12).
Large result set / performance boundary: very large number of audit logs and response-time assertion (TC11).
Query parameter robustness: extra/unknown query param does not break endpoint (TC10).
Regression and backward compatibility: ordering and schema validation tests (TC15, TC16).
Security and accessibility: additional checks for SQLi/XSS and UI accessibility (TC13, TC14, TC17).
gaps: Pagination: no tests for paging (page/limit/offset, next/prev links, total counts) or behavior when the service enforces page size. TC11 stresses size but does not validate paging semantics.
Rate limiting / throttling: no tests for 429 Too Many Requests, Retry-After headers, or burst handling.
Caching / conditional GET: no tests for ETag, If-None-Match / If-Modified-Since, Cache-Control, or 304 Not Modified behavior.
Authorization semantics beyond 401: no tests for 403 Forbidden or role/permission-based access control (insufficient privileges).
Content negotiation and media-type errors: no tests for Accept header variations or unsupported media types (406/415).
Response header validation beyond Content-Type: headers like ETag, Cache-Control, Content-Length, correlation IDs, security headers are not asserted.
Performance / load testing is shallow: TC11 asserts <2s but lacks controlled, reproducible load scenarios and SLAs across percentiles.
Query parameter validation coverage is narrow: only an extra param case is present — invalid/ malformed query params or combinations are not exercised.
recommendations: Add pagination tests (if applicable): verify page & limit parameters, boundaries (0, negative, >max), consistent ordering across pages, and presence/accuracy of next/prev or total-count metadata.
Add rate-limiting tests: send controlled bursts to assert 429 responses and presence/correctness of Retry-After header; include tests per user/IP and combined with authentication.
Add caching/conditional GET tests: assert ETag and Cache-Control headers, perform GET with If-None-Match to get 304, and verify ETag changes after resource updates.
Add permission/authorization tests for 403: exercise authenticated users lacking scope/role to confirm 403 Forbidden and clear error messages; include expired/revoked token scenarios.
Add content-negotiation tests: vary Accept header (e.g., application/xml, */*) and assert proper handling/406 responses when applicable.
Assert important response headers: Content-Length, correlation ID, Date, and security headers where relevant; include schema/type checks for headers used by clients.
Convert TC11 into reproducible performance tests: controlled load, percentiles (p50/p95/p99), and include environment notes so thresholds are meaningful and stable.
Broaden query-parameter tests: invalid values, repeated params, very long values, and combinations to validate robust parameter parsing and error paths.

Move UI-specific accessibility checks (TC17) to the UI test suite; keep API tests focused on data/headers/contract. If kept here, make the expectation explicit that UI rendering is out of scope for API contract tests.
Automate schema validation (TC16) against the canonical #/definitions/AuditLog with strict type/format checks (UUID format, ISO-8601 timestamps) and fail fast on deviations.
